<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-12-05T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-12-05T17:00:00-05:00" n="336" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d336">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/601:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Neville</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-12-05T17:00:00-05:00">December 5, 1929—5
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>124. On December 2, in conversation, I asked the Japanese Ambassador to
                            make clear to Baron Shidehara that our recent action in regard to Russia
                            and China was not taken from any desire to intrude into Manchurian
                            affairs but to save the Kellogg-Briand Pact from losing its strength and
                            force. He said he understood perfectly and would make this clear to his
                            Government. The foregoing merely for your information.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>